{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17617012","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17617012"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:09:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:09:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16450"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16450","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16450"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.9,0.05,0,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9141"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74743"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9141","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9141"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16450"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60228"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1106"},{"type":"tags","id":"1127"},{"type":"tags","id":"1153"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2905"},{"type":"tags","id":"3189"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5871"},{"type":"tags","id":"6344"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21712"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21718"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74743","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74743"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department after a witnessed seizure. The event began with a sudden loss of consciousness and a loud cry. This was followed by a 20-second period of muscle rigidity during which breathing ceased. Subsequently, there was rhythmic jerking of all limbs with laboured breathing, excessive salivation, tongue biting, and urinary incontinence. She regained consciousness after 15 minutes but was initially confused and wanted to sleep. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following is the most likely type of seizure?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Temporal lobe seizure","Generalised tonic-clonic seizure","Myoclonic seizure","Extratemporal seizure","Absence seizure"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe description provided is classic for a \u003Cstrong\u003Egeneralised tonic-clonic seizure\u003C/strong\u003E. These seizures follow a characteristic pattern: initial loss of consciousness (often with a cry), tonic phase (sustained muscle contraction), clonic phase (rhythmic jerking), followed by a post-ictal period of confusion and somnolence. Associated features include tongue biting, urinary incontinence, and excessive salivation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETemporal lobe seizures\u003C/strong\u003E typically begin with an aura (such as d\u00e9j\u00e0 vu, fear, or unusual smells) and may progress to altered awareness with automatisms. They do not typically present with the tonic-clonic sequence described here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMyoclonic seizures\u003C/strong\u003E are brief, shock-like jerks of a muscle or group of muscles, typically lasting a fraction of a second. They do not involve loss of consciousness or a post-ictal phase.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExtratemporal seizures\u003C/strong\u003E originate outside the temporal lobe and have varying presentations depending on the location. They may have motor, sensory, or behavioural manifestations but do not typically follow the classic tonic-clonic pattern.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbsence seizures\u003C/strong\u003E are characterised by brief lapses in awareness (typically 5-10 seconds) with minimal or no motor activity. The person appears to be staring and is unresponsive. There is no post-ictal confusion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A generalised tonic-clonic seizure has a characteristic sequence: aura (optional), loss of consciousness, tonic phase, clonic phase, post-ictal phase.","The post-ictal phase typically includes confusion and somnolence lasting minutes to hours.","Tongue biting and incontinence are common features of generalised tonic-clonic seizures."],"references":["Kammerman S, Wasserman L. Seizure disorders: Part 1. Classification and diagnosis. West J Med. 2001 Aug;175(2):99-103. doi: 10.1136/ewjm.175.2.99. PMID: 11483551; PMCID: PMC1071497","Fisher RS, Cross JH, French JA, Higurashi N, Hirsch E, Jansen FE, Lagae L, Mosh\u00e9 SL, Peltola J, Roulet Perez E, Scheffer IE, Zuberi SM. Operational classification of seizure types by the International League Against Epilepsy: Position Paper of the ILAE Commission for Classification and Terminology. Epilepsia. 2017 Apr;58(4):522-530. doi: 10.1111/epi.13670. Epub 2017 Mar 8. PMID: 28276060","Sarmast ST, Abdullahi AM, Jahan N. Current Classification of Seizures and Epilepsies: Scope, Limitations and Recommendations for Future Action. Cureus. 2020 Sep 20;12(9):e10549. doi: 10.7759/cureus.10549. PMID: 33101797; PMCID: PMC7575300","Huff JS, Murr NI. Seizure. 2023 Feb 7. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 28613516","Tenney JR, Glauser TA. The current state of absence epilepsy: can we have your attention? Epilepsy Curr. 2013 May;13(3):135-40. doi: 10.5698/1535-7511-13.3.135. PMID: 23840175; PMCID: PMC3697883Nass RD, Zur B, Elger CE, Holdenrieder S, Surges R. Acute metabolic effects of tonic-clonic seizures. Epilepsia Open. 2019 Oct 22;4(4):599-608. doi: 10.1002/epi4.12364. PMID: 31819916; PMCID: PMC6885665."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60228"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16450"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60228","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60228"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-26T18:38:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-26T18:39:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9141"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74743"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group